// Demonstrates the MVP class declaration form (2026-04-25).
//
// User direction: "Just make an object class, where an object class
// inherits from an embedding class, and the embedding class just
// inherits from vector. Make it so that the compiler will be able
// to tell what this is."
//
// What this MVP gives you:
// - `class Name extends Parent { }` declarations.
// - Single inheritance, parent chain must bottom out at a primitive
//   (vector / int / float / fuzzy / etc.).
// - The compiler registers each class name and uses the
//   inheritance chain to resolve type-position references.
// - At runtime, instances of user classes are plain vectors —
//   no extra storage, no metadata, no dispatch overhead.
// - Bodies are empty; methods / fields / operator implementations
//   are deferred (see `todo.md` § "Ontology — make the class
//   system real").

class Embedding extends vector { }
class Object extends Embedding { }
class Animal extends Object { }
class Cat extends Animal { }

// The class declarations above are compile-time-only metadata.
// At runtime there is nothing to execute for them — `main` just
// returns a string confirming the program compiled.
function string main() {
    return "ontology demo: Embedding -> Object -> Animal -> Cat";
}
